The first and second cervical vertebrae are structurally and functionally different from other vertebrae. 
A.  C1 is the atlas     ; it supports the skull. The atlas does not have a vertebral body, and thus consists largely of a ring of bone. 
B.  C2 is the axis; it is characterized by the presence of the dens     . The dens is formed during development when the body of C1 becomes fused to that of C2.
in Greek mythology, Atlas supported the heavens on his shoulders, as C1 supports the skull
